WEBVTT

00:32.226 --> 00:36.570
It is nice to be here in Markle on this last Sunday of the year.

00:36.610 --> 00:43.798
And I hope that you have had a Merry Christmas and I want to wish you a Happy New Year as well.

00:44.198 --> 00:45.579
I also want to give you a heads up.

00:46.180 --> 01:00.114
I received a gift this week from someone anonymous, a gift that I was not expecting, a gift that I had not received one like this for quite some time.

01:00.386 --> 01:06.752
a sore throat, congestion, runny nose, the whole nine yards.

01:07.633 --> 01:10.836
And I joked actually last Sunday with Dita.

01:10.917 --> 01:12.378
I don't know if she remembers or not.

01:12.418 --> 01:14.880
We were standing there back by the back doors.

01:15.461 --> 01:19.785
And I said, you know, I think on Friday, I'm going to call Tim and tell him that I'm sick.

01:20.686 --> 01:24.850
And I actually ended up sick this week.

01:24.951 --> 01:28.434
So, be careful what you wish for.

01:29.378 --> 01:32.481
Anyways, it seems to be the gift that keeps on giving.

01:32.662 --> 01:33.763
So bear with me this morning.

01:33.783 --> 01:34.544
I've got my water.

01:34.584 --> 01:37.287
I've got cough drops in my pocket.

01:37.347 --> 01:38.628
I've got tissues up here.

01:38.648 --> 01:41.211
It should be an interesting morning.

01:41.952 --> 01:42.993
But I think we're good to go.

01:43.033 --> 01:45.656
Well, all good things must come to an end.

01:45.676 --> 01:47.478
And here we are at the end of 2025.

01:48.439 --> 01:52.963
And I think most of us are probably looking forward to what's in store for 2026.

01:53.324 --> 01:59.090
And likewise, we're also at the end of our series on 1st Corinthians.

01:59.746 --> 02:05.895
September 21st was when we started this series and the high temperature that day was 83 degrees.

02:06.496 --> 02:12.665
And some of you may be wondering, when are we ever going to get out of this series on first Corinthians?

02:12.725 --> 02:16.190
I mean, seriously, we've been in this thing for a long time.

02:16.891 --> 02:24.763
And it's kind of like when you're on that road trip with your kids in the backseat, you know, and they're asking you, like, how much longer till we get there, dad?

02:25.204 --> 02:27.747
How many of you have been in that situation before?

02:27.788 --> 02:29.490
Yeah.

02:29.890 --> 02:34.817
And if you're like me, my typical response is something like, well, about 20 more minutes.

02:36.359 --> 02:49.076
So, for all of you who've been in this long journey and first Corinthians together, and you're asking that question how much longer, well, my answer to you this morning is about 20 more minutes, okay?

02:51.039 --> 02:59.090
So, hang in there, keep your seatbelt fastened, sit back, relax, enjoy the ride as we unpack this final chapter, chapter 16,

02:59.522 --> 03:01.264
in 1 Corinthians this morning.

03:02.065 --> 03:11.075
Now, when we read 1 Corinthians, we usually focus on the big chapters, like chapters 13, which talks about love, you know?

03:11.856 --> 03:20.506
Or we focus on chapter 15, which Tim preached on last Sunday, which talks about the resurrection, this hope that we have over death.

03:21.047 --> 03:24.110
And it seems like chapter 16 is sort of an afterthought.

03:24.731 --> 03:27.474
Paul mentions his travel plans,

03:27.586 --> 03:36.097
Some names that we don't really know, some greetings we don't fully understand, and the whole chapter just feels a little bit disconnected from the rest of the letter.

03:36.958 --> 03:39.561
It's like a chapter of misfit toys, okay?

03:40.462 --> 03:52.978
But as we walk through this chapter together this morning, I think you'll see that there are some really valuable lessons that we can take away, especially as we think about moving forward into 2026.

03:53.346 --> 04:00.796
We've been walking together through first Corinthians for the past few months, and in this letter, Paul is riding to a church that is struggling.

04:01.337 --> 04:08.667
They're struggling with division, they're struggling with pride, they're struggling with confusion, and the pressure of the culture around them.

04:09.348 --> 04:13.854
And from the start, Paul reminds them that the church is not built around one person.

04:13.934 --> 04:19.762
It's not built around Apollo's or Paul or Peter, it is built around

04:19.970 --> 04:25.597
Christ, and he urges them to go back to what unites them in the first place, which is the gospel.

04:26.198 --> 04:30.823
And he even challenges them to lay down their rights for the sake of others.

04:31.604 --> 04:40.556
He also addresses in this letter their misuse of spiritual gifts and reminds them that love is what really defines a Christian.

04:41.317 --> 04:48.946
And then Paul points them to the resurrection and the hope that we have in Christ and this hope of eternal life, which

04:49.186 --> 04:50.989
Tim again preached on last week.

04:51.690 --> 04:56.697
And so now moving into chapter 16, here we get a glimpse of God's heart for the poor.

04:56.757 --> 05:03.346
We get a glimpse of what it means to trust him with our plans and a glimpse of how important love really is.

05:03.847 --> 05:11.078
Chapter 16 is like the gospel with boots on, showing us how to live out our faith in a very practical way.

05:11.919 --> 05:16.946
But before we dive into this chapter, let's go to the Lord in prayer.

05:18.178 --> 05:23.924
Father, thank you so much for the opportunity to learn from your word.

05:24.325 --> 05:29.851
And I pray, Lord, that our ears would be open to hear what you have to say this morning.

05:30.452 --> 05:40.402
And I pray, Lord, despite not feeling the best, Lord, I pray that the words of my mouth and the things in my heart would be pleasing to you.

05:40.843 --> 05:42.345
Let me pray this in Jesus' name.

05:42.985 --> 05:43.306
Amen.

05:45.348 --> 05:47.250
So we begin chapter 16.

05:47.490 --> 05:55.223
in this book with Paul giving us some directions regarding how the Corinthians should organize their collection for the poor.

05:55.984 --> 06:07.303
And then this is the first of three or four instances in Paul's letters where he talks about taking up a collection for these poor saints or these poor believers in Jerusalem.

06:07.864 --> 06:13.714
And just to give you a little bit of background here, if we go back to Galatians chapter two,

06:14.050 --> 06:21.721
We see that Peter, James, and John had kind of given Paul their stamp of approval, so to speak, to go and reach the Gentiles.

06:22.081 --> 06:31.694
He only asked that he remember the poor, and which Paul says that he is very eager to do so, especially these poor believers in Jerusalem.

06:32.635 --> 06:35.179
Now this passage doesn't explain why they were poor.

06:35.740 --> 06:41.468
We know from Acts chapter 11 that there was a famine going on at this time, and maybe that's why they were poor.

06:42.108 --> 06:43.250
We also know that

06:43.426 --> 06:49.532
A lot of Jews were persecuting Jews that chose to follow Jesus, and maybe that's why they were poor.

06:49.892 --> 06:57.800
Whatever the case, what we do know is that there's poor believers in Jerusalem, and Paul is eager to help them out.

06:58.221 --> 07:02.545
And so he gives the Corinthians some instructions on how to do this.

07:03.386 --> 07:11.954
And we'll look now in starting in 1 Corinthians chapter 16, verses one through

07:12.610 --> 07:14.733
Let me grab a quick drink here.

07:19.078 --> 07:23.003
It says, now about the collection for the Lord's people.

07:24.045 --> 07:25.907
Do what I told the Galatian churches to do.

07:26.007 --> 07:32.215
On the first day of every week, each of you should set aside a sum of money and keeping with your income.

07:32.956 --> 07:37.362
Saving it up so that when I come, no collections will have to be made.

07:37.954 --> 07:44.484
Then when I arrive, I will give letters of introduction to the menu approved and send them with your gift to Jerusalem.

07:45.605 --> 07:50.112
If it seems advisable for me to go also, they will accompany me.

07:51.214 --> 07:56.782
So at first glance, these verses seem pretty straightforward, some simple instructions about giving.

07:58.084 --> 08:07.538
But to better understand what's going on here, we need to look and say, see how these first four verses in 1 Corinthians chapter 16 and

08:07.682 --> 08:19.713
Second Corinthians chapters 8 and 9 tie together because both of these are talking about the same collection for the same poor believers in Jerusalem.

08:20.534 --> 08:32.005
So here in 1 Corinthians 16, this passage that we just read, we see that Paul tells the church to set aside money each week so that the gift would be ready to be delivered when Paul arrived.

08:33.166 --> 08:37.490
But what the passage doesn't tell you is that as time passed,

08:38.018 --> 08:43.686
The Corinthians had some bumps along the way, and they failed to fall through on the collection.

08:44.467 --> 08:59.247
And so Paul writes a second letter to the Corinthians, and in chapters eight and nine, he addresses this problem, and he tells them to finish what they started.

08:59.367 --> 09:07.698
So rather than giving them instructions, he really gives them encouragement, and he reminds them of the generosity

09:07.874 --> 09:16.162
of the other churches in the area, and he reached the whole idea of giving and how much Jesus loves us and has given everything for us.

09:16.883 --> 09:32.699
Second Corinthians chapter eight verse nine says it this way, that though he was rich, talking about Jesus here, that though he was rich, yet for your sake, he became poor so that you, through his poverty, might become rich.

09:33.539 --> 09:36.082
So again, first Corinthians 16 teaches us

09:36.194 --> 09:38.857
how to give, which is the passage we're gonna be looking at this morning.

09:38.877 --> 09:47.948
2 Corinthians 8 and 9 teaches us why we are to give, because God has been above and beyond generous to us.

09:49.470 --> 09:52.434
And this brings us up to this week, Christmas.

09:55.678 --> 10:01.725
For a lot of people, Christmas is all about Santa gifts and what's under the tree, right?

10:03.127 --> 10:05.650
But what is the real reason for this season?

10:05.730 --> 10:07.513
I mean, why do we celebrate Christmas?

10:07.573 --> 10:09.756
Why do we give gifts at all?

10:10.257 --> 10:13.181
We give because God gave first.

10:13.842 --> 10:15.424
He gave us the greatest gift of all.

10:15.905 --> 10:18.148
Like Corbin said, his son Jesus Christ.

10:18.168 --> 10:23.156
And that's exactly even why the wise men came looking for Jesus.

10:24.037 --> 10:32.690
Matthew tells us in Matthew chapter two, on coming to the house, they saw the child with his mother Mary and they bowed down and worshiped him.

10:32.866 --> 10:38.615
and they opened their treasures and presented him with gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh.

10:39.336 --> 10:51.394
And I want you to notice something here, and that is that their giving of frankincense or gold frankincense and myrrh was an expression of their worship.

10:51.414 --> 10:54.639
And that's Paul's message to us as well.

10:54.759 --> 10:57.583
The giving is an act of worship.

10:58.264 --> 10:59.766
It's not a financial decision.

10:59.907 --> 11:02.130
It's not a business transaction.

11:02.370 --> 11:06.014
or a fundraising strategy or a tax write-off.

11:06.034 --> 11:09.118
Proposed generosity is all about worship.

11:09.178 --> 11:13.743
It's something deeply spiritual and it reveals what's in a person's heart.

11:15.204 --> 11:21.712
Matthew 621 says, for where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.

11:22.252 --> 11:23.974
And I think the reverse is also true.

11:24.034 --> 11:27.498
For where your heart is, there your treasure will be also.

11:28.639 --> 11:31.122
And we see throughout the Bible that God's heart

11:31.330 --> 11:32.292
is for the poor.

11:32.973 --> 11:36.098
But the question is, where is our heart?

11:36.158 --> 11:37.580
Where is our treasure?

11:38.161 --> 11:41.286
We live in a culture where money drives so much of life.

11:41.726 --> 11:45.512
What kind of job can I get that will help me earn the most money?

11:45.613 --> 11:49.839
Or how can I set myself up to be financially secure?

11:49.899 --> 11:55.909
Even our reputation and our identity are often wrapped up around money.

11:56.630 --> 11:59.154
And we have to admit it, we are materialistic.

11:59.522 --> 12:02.706
And yet to most of us, it really doesn't mean a thing.

12:03.047 --> 12:03.528
So what?

12:03.628 --> 12:04.188
Who cares?

12:04.429 --> 12:05.170
Life goes on.

12:05.230 --> 12:06.592
Eat, drink, and be married.

12:07.773 --> 12:10.337
They say that in America, we invent needs.

12:10.597 --> 12:13.842
It's like we didn't know we needed something until we saw it.

12:14.102 --> 12:23.936
As I was looking for gifts on Amazon this past month, I came across several items like the mini handheld chainsaw or the personal soft serve ice cream maker.

12:24.477 --> 12:27.020
And I immediately said my head, I need that.

12:27.441 --> 12:28.402
How many of you?

12:28.802 --> 12:31.025
Did the same thing, yeah.

12:32.107 --> 12:37.234
I even bought one item and had this written on the box.

12:38.235 --> 12:41.279
The one gadget you didn't know you needed.

12:42.161 --> 12:44.464
The one gadget you didn't know you needed.

12:44.504 --> 12:46.567
That phrase says a lot about us.

12:47.528 --> 12:51.794
It reveals how quickly we are drawn to things that we don't even need.

12:52.546 --> 12:59.453
Too often our treasures are focused on our needs, our needs, our desires, rather than on the needs of others.

12:59.553 --> 13:02.215
Our minds are consumed by what's happening in our world.

13:03.056 --> 13:19.031
We're already planning our next vacation for next year, and we're thinking about what's new restaurant we wanna try that we haven't been to yet, and we're considering how we wanna make that upgrade to our house, and we're wondering when is the next iPhone gonna be released?

13:19.672 --> 13:21.874
Now, none of those things are evil in themselves,

13:22.210 --> 13:23.091
That's not the issue.

13:23.131 --> 13:30.241
The issue is, how are we stewarding the things that God has entrusted to us?

13:32.184 --> 13:38.473
Back in 1 Corinthians 16, Paul tells the believers to set aside their gifts on the first day of every week.

13:38.493 --> 13:42.318
In other words, giving is meant to be thoughtful and regular.

13:42.759 --> 13:47.005
It isn't something we do only when we feel moved or when we happen to have something left over.

13:47.486 --> 13:50.610
It's not coming to church and pulling out your wallet and just

13:50.754 --> 13:53.999
you know, thumbing through and dropping a few bills in the offering plate.

13:54.640 --> 13:58.385
But rather, it's supposed to be a spiritual rhythm of our lives.

13:58.505 --> 14:08.380
We're supposed to be people who give first, not last, who see our generosity not as a loss of what we have, but as a way to live like Jesus.

14:09.261 --> 14:13.227
If you think about it, the kingdom of God is really kind of an upside down kingdom.

14:14.028 --> 14:18.034
The world is telling us, take, take, take in the more you take, the more you'll have.

14:18.786 --> 14:21.630
But God is really encouraging us to give, give, give.

14:21.890 --> 14:25.355
And the more we give, the more we will be blessed.

14:25.375 --> 14:31.344
Now maybe not with material possessions, but with his provision nonetheless.

14:31.524 --> 14:38.093
Because ultimately, it's about trusting God with what is already his to begin with.

14:39.675 --> 14:42.780
So that raises an important question here in this passage.

14:43.821 --> 14:47.346
How much were the people actually supposed to give in the first place?

14:48.066 --> 14:56.898
Was it A, $5, B, a widow's mite, C, everything they owned, or D, 10%.

14:58.320 --> 15:03.127
Well, if you look at verse two, it simply says, in keeping with your income.

15:04.189 --> 15:05.390
Sounds kind of vague, doesn't it?

15:06.212 --> 15:07.493
Just in keeping with your income.

15:07.834 --> 15:09.316
There's no mention of tithing here.

15:09.817 --> 15:16.466
The gift is simply meant to reflect what each person has in proportion to how much they have been blessed by God.

15:16.962 --> 15:28.558
2 Corinthians 8, 12 puts it this way, for if the willingness is there, the gift is acceptable according to what one has, not according to what one does not have.

15:29.879 --> 15:36.849
So this gift is to be thoughtful, planned, set aside, and proportional to what each person had.

15:37.510 --> 15:46.802
And what I want you to see is that in these first opening verses of chapter 16, Paul shows us that generosity is not an afterthought, but it is

15:47.074 --> 15:50.478
and act of worship in response to God's grace.

15:51.138 --> 16:00.309
And when we give, we are declaring that our trust isn't in our money or in our security, but in a God who's already given us everything in Christ.

16:00.929 --> 16:10.860
And if we as a church can learn to live this way, if we can learn to give this way, man, we can be such a testimony of God's love to those around us.

16:11.621 --> 16:16.146
And it can transform our hearts into reflecting God's heart

16:16.610 --> 16:21.337
rather than the values that we see in the world around us.

16:22.699 --> 16:41.988
All right, before Paul completely wraps things up here in 1 Corinthians 16, he goes on in verses five through 12 to talk briefly about his travel plans and the people he's gonna be doing ministry with, people like Apollos and Timothy and others.

16:42.349 --> 16:45.714
And I don't wanna spend a lot of time on this section this morning

16:45.954 --> 16:50.120
But I do want us to look at a couple verses, verses six and seven.

16:51.041 --> 17:05.220
It says this, perhaps I will stay with you for a while or even spend the winter so you can help me with my journey wherever I go, for I do not want to see you now and make only passing visit.

17:05.240 --> 17:09.185
I hope to spend some time with you if the Lord permits.

17:09.986 --> 17:15.794
All right, it's Paul's talking about his travel plans and he says things like, perhaps I'll stay with you.

17:16.130 --> 17:20.595
I hope to spend some time with you if the Lord permits.

17:20.615 --> 17:26.603
See, Paul makes his plans, but he also leaves room for God to redirect them if needed.

17:27.263 --> 17:37.416
And I can tell you more than once, if you look throughout Paul's letters here, more than once, God in fact did redirect Paul's plans.

17:38.377 --> 17:46.066
They say that to be a missionary, you have to be flexible, which may be true, but it doesn't mean it's easy.

17:47.746 --> 17:55.053
I would say for many of us and myself included, being flexible isn't really convenient.

17:55.093 --> 17:58.556
We like our five-year plans, our calendars, books, months out.

17:58.957 --> 18:00.318
We like clear outcomes.

18:00.378 --> 18:02.480
We like to be in control of our time.

18:03.221 --> 18:09.567
But as my friend Bugu Dogo in Molly says, each day has its own reality.

18:10.027 --> 18:13.911
And there are a lot of days in ministry where things don't always go as plans.

18:15.452 --> 18:17.554
A couple of years ago,

18:23.138 --> 18:29.829
Couple years ago, I was heading back to a village, and I don't know why I'm getting choked up over this.

18:32.213 --> 18:46.738
I was heading back to a village to drop off a pastor, and as we were driving, a lady flagged us down on the side of the road and asked us to stop and pray for her granddaughter, Marie.

18:47.874 --> 18:54.384
Now I'm guessing that doesn't happen to you very often, where you're driving down the road and someone flags you down and asks you to pray for them.

19:00.373 --> 19:17.298
But Marie is a 17-year-old girl who was running, playing,

19:17.986 --> 19:28.559
Acting like every other 17-year-old girl, her age, until one day when her life changed when she had an accident.

19:29.199 --> 19:41.194
She fell from a third story building and she landed on some rebar which pierced her back and left her paralyzed from the waist down.

19:44.217 --> 19:44.978
Just awful.

19:47.714 --> 19:51.100
And so here we are, we get flagged down to pray for this girl.

19:51.420 --> 19:56.729
And I'm thinking to myself, what are we doing?

19:57.811 --> 20:00.796
I don't have a real my calendar today.

20:00.836 --> 20:02.419
She's not part of my agenda.

20:02.439 --> 20:05.183
She's not part of my five-year ministry plan.

20:10.592 --> 20:13.938
These are from my nose, not from my eyes.

20:18.370 --> 20:22.014
But you know, that's sometimes how God works.

20:24.457 --> 20:32.587
And that time spent praying for her led to a continued relationship with her and her family to this day.

20:35.231 --> 20:39.776
Recently, Marie's been blessed to have a new porch that's handicapped friendly.

20:45.243 --> 20:47.986
She has a new bed, a new wheelchair.

20:48.258 --> 21:02.032
Thanks to generous donors, and Stuja has been above and beyond amazing to this little girl, and has even had other American physical therapists come over and speak into a world.

21:02.092 --> 21:11.241
And most importantly, she's hearing about Jesus, and she is already taking some bold steps to accepting his grace.

21:13.724 --> 21:16.146
And that's the thing, loving people

21:16.770 --> 21:20.356
Rarely fits into our calendar in a nice way.

21:20.416 --> 21:22.519
It's oftentimes very messy.

21:24.983 --> 21:28.749
I think being flexible is just love and action.

21:30.071 --> 21:32.996
It's saying to people like Marie, hey, you matter.

21:33.036 --> 21:34.919
You matter more than my schedule.

21:35.279 --> 21:41.970
It's choosing people over plans and choosing to be present in people's lives over our agendas.

21:43.458 --> 21:45.741
Let's bring this now to verses 13 and 14.

21:45.761 --> 21:46.942
I've got to keep moving on.

21:47.003 --> 21:48.905
Otherwise I'll be here in tears all day.

21:50.767 --> 21:50.968
All right.

21:50.988 --> 21:54.052
13 and 14.

21:54.913 --> 21:56.254
Paul says, be on your guard.

21:56.315 --> 21:57.596
Stand firm in the faith.

21:57.676 --> 21:58.377
Be courageous.

21:58.437 --> 21:59.098
Be strong.

21:59.138 --> 22:01.301
Do everything in love.

22:02.062 --> 22:08.370
Five short commands that are very practical, not just for the Corinthians, but for us as well.

22:08.802 --> 22:11.146
First he says, be on your guard.

22:11.226 --> 22:14.972
To be on your guard means to be watchful, to be spiritually alert.

22:15.072 --> 22:19.159
It's the same word that he uses in 1 Peter when he says be alert.

22:20.081 --> 22:25.349
In a sober mind, you're interviewing the devil prowls around like a roaring lion looking for someone to devour.

22:25.409 --> 22:30.638
Being on your guard is really important, especially in a world that is dulling our senses.

22:31.299 --> 22:35.506
Even today, the prince of this world is looking for someone like you to devour.

22:36.162 --> 22:40.849
Before writing this letter to the Corinthians, Paul had spent a year and a half with them.

22:41.650 --> 22:51.704
He left some serious, and after, sorry, after he left, some serious moral problems began to surface in the church.

22:52.104 --> 22:57.692
Hold on a second.

22:57.712 --> 22:59.154
See, I knew I brought these for a reason.

23:01.237 --> 23:04.562
So Paul, these Corinth and afterwards,

23:05.058 --> 23:06.660
The church is really struggling.

23:08.161 --> 23:10.885
And I don't believe that these things just happened overnight.

23:11.325 --> 23:17.692
Little by little, things like pride and sexual promiscuity and division just kind of crept into the world.

23:18.553 --> 23:21.577
It certainly sounds a lot like our culture today, doesn't it?

23:22.317 --> 23:30.066
I mean, Sujanai, every time we come back, we are kind of shocked by the spiritual decline that we keep seeing in America right now.

23:30.338 --> 23:39.850
And we're just a shock to find out how many people that we once considered brothers and sisters in Christ have been swept away by the culture and have abandoned the faith completely.

23:41.192 --> 23:42.654
Maybe you know somebody like that.

23:43.375 --> 23:46.058
So it's important for us to be on our guard and watchful.

23:46.078 --> 23:48.781
It means paying attention to what molds and shapes us.

23:49.783 --> 23:53.968
I mean, ask yourself, is it scriptures or is it my screens that are shaping my life?

23:54.749 --> 23:56.491
Is it prayer or is it politics?

23:56.551 --> 23:58.674
Is it our comfort or is it

23:59.010 --> 24:00.753
our relationship with Jesus Christ.

24:02.896 --> 24:07.763
Next in this series of commands that Paul gives us, he says, stand firm in the faith.

24:07.804 --> 24:11.008
And standing firm means holding fast to the truth of the gospel.

24:11.669 --> 24:17.619
When I'm teaching farmers in Africa, we encourage them to stake their claim, much like they would stake out a field.

24:18.400 --> 24:27.634
Farmers go around and they put stakes on the corners of the field to mark their property boundaries, to say, in that moment, this is my field.

24:27.778 --> 24:30.703
It's not my neighbors, it's not anyone else's, this is my field.

24:30.943 --> 24:40.237
And in a similar way, we encourage these farmers to stake out their lives for Jesus, to say, my life belongs to him and no one else.

24:40.698 --> 24:48.470
So another farmer's are making fun of you or your family or your rejection because you've left your Islamic faith, it's time to stake your claim in him.

24:49.031 --> 24:51.795
And that's what it means to stand firm and the faith.

24:52.717 --> 24:56.242
But standing firm in our culture, man, that's tough.

24:56.514 --> 24:59.637
and even say no to our own desires is not easy.

25:00.478 --> 25:00.799
C.S.

25:00.839 --> 25:05.824
Lewis says, we are not necessarily doubting that God will do the best for us.

25:06.645 --> 25:10.049
We are wondering how painful the best will turn out to be.

25:10.690 --> 25:17.377
And sometimes, telling you, standing firm in our faith means trusting God even when His best will be hard.

25:18.038 --> 25:23.785
It means being obedient even when it comes at a cost.

25:23.805 --> 25:25.106
Next to this series,

25:25.506 --> 25:26.968
says be courageous.

25:27.549 --> 25:32.976
And I don't know which version of the Bible you're using, but some versions say act like men, okay?

25:34.138 --> 25:40.226
Courage, as Paul refers to here in this verse, is not about self-confidence or relying on her own strength.

25:41.027 --> 25:48.597
It's true courage is confidence in Christ and his work on the cross, knowing that the one who defeated sin and death is with us.

25:49.378 --> 25:52.242
And then he says in this series, be strong.

25:52.386 --> 25:56.131
Paul's command to be strong again is not mustering up our own strength.

25:56.712 --> 26:01.658
Paul is saying be strengthened, not make yourself strong.

26:02.520 --> 26:10.350
It's like he says in Ephesians chapter six verse 10, finally be strong in the Lord and in his mighty power.

26:10.851 --> 26:16.038
In other words, his strength is fountain in the Lord and in his mighty power, not in our own strength.

26:16.759 --> 26:19.742
Strength doesn't come from trying harder or digging deeper.

26:19.783 --> 26:22.386
It comes from the spirit of God working

26:22.754 --> 26:23.215
in us.

26:24.437 --> 26:29.265
And then finally he says, do everything in love.

26:30.787 --> 26:36.096
Paul wraps up the letter with the key principle for living as a faithful follower of Jesus.

26:36.376 --> 26:37.538
And that is love.

26:38.119 --> 26:45.151
And it really echoes what he said in 1 Corinthians chapter 13, the famous love chapter.

26:45.211 --> 26:49.618
Now he doesn't mean just having nice, warm, fuzzy feelings for someone.

26:49.954 --> 26:53.899
Maybe like Scotland is having for Cindy today as they celebrate their anniversary.

26:54.380 --> 26:55.041
Where is Scott?

26:55.061 --> 26:55.502
Is he here?

26:56.603 --> 26:57.124
There he is.

26:57.725 --> 26:57.925
All right.

26:58.586 --> 27:00.508
That's not what he's talking about, Scott.

27:01.309 --> 27:07.698
He means every action, every word, every part of life should be shaped by God's love.

27:07.758 --> 27:14.027
A love that is selfless and sacrificial, a love that is patient, kind, seeking the ultimate good of others.

27:14.127 --> 27:19.314
A love that mirrors God's love for humanity as we talked about in 1 Corinthians chapter 13.

27:19.714 --> 27:22.497
A love that focuses on serving others, forgiving others.

27:22.977 --> 27:26.421
A love that is based on truth rather than on feelings.

27:27.282 --> 27:29.464
Paul says here, do everything in love.

27:29.805 --> 27:33.108
He's also including all the problems that the Corinthians were dealing with.

27:34.049 --> 27:36.652
They're quarrels on divisions in chapters one through three.

27:36.692 --> 27:40.095
They're bad attitudes towards Paul in chapter four and nine.

27:40.136 --> 27:42.778
The lawsuits between the believers in chapter six.

27:43.339 --> 27:46.322
The struggles in marriage and singleness in chapter seven

27:46.562 --> 27:57.278
the abuse of the weak in chapters eight through 10, the mistreatment of the have-nots at the Lord's Supper and the failure to build up the church through spiritual gifts in chapters 12 through 14.

27:57.899 --> 28:06.973
Paul's basically saying, hey, Corinthians, if love were guiding all of your actions, then these problems would not have existed.

28:07.914 --> 28:12.902
And I believe for us, this is our path forward into 2026.

28:13.703 --> 28:15.506
First, to truly grasp

28:16.002 --> 28:26.894
how deeply God loves us, and then let that love flow out of us into those around us, both in word and deed, do everything in love.

28:27.975 --> 28:41.010
In a world full division in politics and even our own families and those closest to us, our first response should be patience, listening, and reconciliation, not trying to win the argument.

28:41.730 --> 28:50.305
When standing up for a truth in our society, it should never be about pride or personal victory, but about caring for the needs of others and honoring God.

28:51.066 --> 28:57.757
And just because we have certain freedoms as America, this doesn't give us a license or a right to just blast everybody on our Facebook page.

28:58.899 --> 29:03.908
But rather, there are opportunities to serve, build up, encourage, and bless others.

29:04.469 --> 29:07.474
Do everything in love.

29:07.586 --> 29:13.113
So Paul finishes the chapter off with some final greeting, starting in verse 21 here.

29:13.173 --> 29:17.458
Does I Paul write this greeting in my own hand?

29:17.779 --> 29:21.543
If anyone does not love the Lord, let that person be cursed.

29:22.385 --> 29:26.169
Come Lord, the grace of the Lord Jesus be with you.

29:26.750 --> 29:30.975
My love to all of you in Christ Jesus, amen.

29:32.137 --> 29:33.138
It's interesting.

29:33.762 --> 29:40.430
Even after all the correcting and disciplining that Paul does in this letter, he closes it as he began with grace.

29:40.530 --> 29:42.553
The grace of the Lord Jesus be with you.

29:43.274 --> 29:46.518
And at the end of the day, the gospel comes down to just that, right?

29:46.738 --> 29:47.178
Grace.

29:47.279 --> 29:50.983
God's undeserved gift for us in Christ Jesus.

29:51.764 --> 29:59.213
And then Paul finishes the letter by adding, my love to all of you in Christ Jesus, amen.

30:00.234 --> 30:03.218
That statement is pretty incredible if you stop and think about it.

30:03.650 --> 30:06.734
I mean, the Corinthians were not easy people to love.

30:07.415 --> 30:08.917
They were difficult to shepherd.

30:09.338 --> 30:11.641
They didn't listen to what Paul told them to do.

30:12.121 --> 30:13.063
They were messy.

30:13.103 --> 30:14.024
They were divided.

30:14.104 --> 30:17.869
They were prideful and immature, and yet Paul ends with love.

30:18.710 --> 30:19.772
How crazy is that?

30:21.434 --> 30:24.719
But he's able to love because this love comes from God.

30:24.799 --> 30:33.170
And as we step into 2026, again, my hope and challenge for you again is this, to truly grasp how deeply God

30:33.378 --> 30:41.389
loves us and then let that love flow out of us into those around us and both word and D do everything in love.

30:42.130 --> 30:52.544
Now, I'm not sure all of us have truly grasped how much God loves us or maybe we've forgotten or maybe we simply take it for granted.

30:53.325 --> 31:02.418
But sometime this week, just stop, slow down, consider ponder

31:03.074 --> 31:11.042
How deeply God loves you, reflecting on all that he has done for you.

31:12.083 --> 31:15.707
It's not something to just understand, but it's also something to live out.

31:16.328 --> 31:26.659
Love is choosing to give thoughtfully and faithfully like we talked about this morning, not just with what's left over, but to give intentionally and to help someone in need.

31:26.719 --> 31:30.002
Love is seeing your gift as an active worship to God.

31:30.370 --> 31:31.632
Love is giving of your time.

31:31.692 --> 31:35.438
It's being flexible and available for God to redirect your path.

31:35.878 --> 31:45.833
For some of you, it means taking time to be present in your children's lives or listening to them, or it may mean volunteering when you know you don't have the time to do it.

31:46.674 --> 31:49.759
Love is living courageously and standing firm in your faith.

31:49.819 --> 31:53.004
It's putting God first, choosing to love Him above all else.

31:53.725 --> 31:56.449
It's having the courage to share the good news with your coworkers.

31:56.489 --> 32:00.114
It's saying no to the cultural pressures around you.

32:00.194 --> 32:02.437
stand in opposition to Godly values.

32:03.098 --> 32:11.130
Love is choosing obedience even when it is costly because you know that God is with you.

32:11.991 --> 32:14.114
So do everything in love.

32:15.075 --> 32:23.147
And really, is there not a better example of this than God himself?

32:25.551 --> 32:27.954
And Christmas reminds us of that love.

32:28.834 --> 32:30.577
How God loved the world.

32:30.617 --> 32:33.220
It's Corbin Porter pointed out this morning.

32:33.240 --> 32:41.652
How God loved the world so much that he gave his one and only son, whoever believes in him should not perish but have eternal life.

32:42.714 --> 32:56.594
And each week we celebrate this love by taking the bread and the cup to remember that Christ came into the world as a humble baby, as a human being, that his love was fully displayed to us

32:56.866 --> 32:58.849
through his life and death on the cross.

32:59.670 --> 33:06.639
And that today we live in a hope because of the resurrection, knowing that Jesus will indeed come again.

33:06.659 --> 33:13.148
So let's remember him now with thankful hearts, grateful of the grace and love that he has given to us.

33:14.189 --> 33:21.719
And at this time, I'm just gonna give you a moment to kind of meditate and to chew on how deeply God loves us.

33:22.580 --> 33:26.866
Think about the sacrifice he made by giving up the glories of heaven to come down to this earth.

33:27.298 --> 33:29.544
and dying for us on a cross.

33:30.767 --> 33:33.374
For you, just think about that.

33:34.517 --> 33:41.234
And then after a moment, we'll take the bread and the cup together.

34:11.874 --> 34:18.084
Alright, at this time, let's take this bread remembering his body which was given for us.

34:30.745 --> 34:35.954
And likewise, let's take the cup to remember his blood that was poured out for us.

34:44.162 --> 34:44.683
Let's pray.

34:49.448 --> 35:01.700
Father, thankful for what you have done for us on the cross, God, we come before you right now asking that you would help us to grasp how wide, how long, how high, how deep is your love.

35:02.261 --> 35:04.083
She pointed out in Ephesians.

35:06.786 --> 35:10.770
God help us to do everything in love, reflecting your love.

35:13.026 --> 35:14.270
Thank you for your forgiveness.

35:16.236 --> 35:20.670
God, we celebrate you what you've done for us today.

35:21.694 --> 35:23.058
Jesus name, amen.

